article.description: Grubin scored eight of her 13 points in the final two minutes as the Mercury extended the longest season-starting skid in WNBA history, beating the 0-8 Shock 70-67 Thursday night.
article.headline: Shock's Grubin scores eight in final two minutes
article.linkText: Mercury's late rally extends Shock's miserable start to record 0-8
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Gordana Grubin wasn't surprised that the Phoenix Mercury made up a double-figures deficit against Detroit. Just delighted.

Grubin scored eight of her 13 points in the final two minutes as the Mercury extended the longest season-starting skid in WNBA history, beating the 0-8 Shock 70-67 Thursday night.

"That was a huge comeback,'' said Grubin, who had a career-high seven assists. "But we've been doing that all year. You never give up on a game. At the end we had a huge 3-pointer from Jennifer (Gillom), and Brandy Reed had that huge rebound.''

Reed had 14 points for the Mercury, 4-1 for the first time since
1998.

She made two crucial plays in the final 16 seconds. She shot
down the lane to grab an offensive rebound after teammate Tracy
Reid missed her second straight free throw while the Mercury were
protecting a 69-67 lead, and then stole the ball from rookie Lenae
Williams with 3.8 seconds left.

That kept it away from Detroit's Swin Cash, who was 4-of-5 from
3-point range and scored 19 points.

"She hadn't taken a lot of shots in the game, and I figured she
might be nervous and miss, so I just tried to time it,'' said Reed,
who is endearing herself with fans again after being suspended most
of last year. "And the steal was my favorite. I figured I'd get
free throws, but they didn't have time to foul.''

Wendy Palmer had 20 points for the Shock, and Astou
Ndiaye-Diatta had 11 points and seven rebounds.

Gillom had 15 points and eight rebounds for Phoenix.

The Shock, who have blown double-figures leads four times this
season, had been tied with the 1999 Cleveland Rockers for the
league's worst start.

"I just think it was a mental breakdown,'' Palmer said. "They are a good team, and they weathered our storm.''

Detroit had a 17-point lead in the first half and led 43-33 at
the break.

But Gillom pulled the Mercury within 60-57 with a 3-pointer with
4:35 to go, and Reed hit an 8-foot jumper 47 seconds later, leaving
Detroit up 60-59.

Grubin, scoreless at halftime, tied it at 62 with a free throw
to start the final 2:00, gave Phoenix a 65-64 lead with two free
throws with 1:17 to go and stole the ball for a layup 17 seconds
later.

She had three more free throws down the stretch.

Cash, who had four points until then, made three 3-pointers in a
2:11 span late in the first half -- the third giving the Shock a
42-25 lead.
	   
"I don't think our legs were heavy at the end,'' said Cash, who
led Connecticut to the national title two months ago. "We have a
young team, but we're getting mature with every game.''
